DGfS 2017, Saarbrcken

Introduction

Variationist approach to grammar

  • Linguistic variables are conditioned by multiple constraints
  • Grammatical knowledge includes implicit knowledge of the quantitative associations (probabilities) between variables and their constraints ( 'variable rules')
  • This knowledge is (in large part) derived from experience, and an individuals grammar is subtly (re)constructed throughout their lifetime
  • Individuals within a community converge on shared norms for constraint effects ( 'orderly heterogeneity')

Different constraints different grammars

Shared Constraints Hypothesis:
Individuals within a community share a set of constraints on variable processes (Guy 2004, 2015)

Grammatical Differences Hypothesis:
Having different constraint effects means having a different grammar, and generally that means belonging to a different speech community

  • Internal contraints are generally thought to be independent of stylistic factors (e.g. Labov 2010)
  • What varies across users in stylistic practice is the overall rate of use of a variant

What is the scope of stylistic variation?

Register: "A variety of a language that is associated with particular functional or situational features[…]"

  • more expansive definition than just formality or attention to speech (see also Rickford 2014)
  • encompasses variability across all speaking and writing practices that make up the entire repertoire of a community
  • variability across registers—esp. written registers—is (relatively) uncharted territory in variationist research (but see, e.g., Hinrichs & Szmrecsanyi 2007; Jankowski 2013; Grafmiller 2014; Pijpops & Van de Velde 2014)

Today's talk

Investigate the sensitivity of a linguistic variable (English genitives) to register effects

Research questions

  1. To what extent are internal contraints sensitive to stylistic variation?
    • do we find register-specific changes in factor effects?
  2. Do individual speakers/writers vary in their use of certain constraints?
    • how consistent are users w.r.t. certain factors?
    • can we find evidence that speakers vary constraint effects
  3. How much can such investigations tell us about the possible existence of register-specific grammars

Case study

English genitive alternation

  1. the best interest of both governments [of-genitive]

  2. both governments' best interest [s-genitive]


Well-researched phenomenon (Rosenbach 2014)

  • relatively stable across regional varieties (Heller et al. 2017)
  • historically quite variable (Wolk et al. 2013)
  • evidence for recent parallel increases in use of s-genitives across vernacular AmE and newspaper writing (Biber 2003; Hundt & Mair 1999; Hinrichs & Szmrecsanyi 2007)
  • variation in other written registers not so well-studied (cf. Grafmiller 2014)

Data: Brown family of corpora

Parallel corpora of 20thC. written US and UK English, sampled across 30-year time spans (Francis & Kucera 1979; Mair & Ludwigs 1999)

  • 1900 > 1930 (B-Brown) > 1960 (Brown) > 1990 (Frown)
  • include data from 15 registers/genres
  • approx. 1 million words per corpus

Present dataset (N = 5096)

Focus on 5 registers of US English from the 1960s (Brown) & 1990s (Frown)

  • Press: newspaper reportage
  • Learned: academic books & papers
  • Non-fiction: memoirs, biographies, letters
  • General fiction
  • Adventure fiction: e.g. westerns

Extract all instances of interchangeable genitives (Rosenbach 2002; Hinrichs & Szmrecsanyi 2007; Grafmiller 2014)

Distribution of genitives by time and genre

Factors coded for

  • Possessor animacy (animate vs. inanimate)
  • Possessor/possessum length in words
  • Possessor NP type (proper vs. common)
  • Final sibilant (Y/N)
  • Possessor givenness (given vs. new)
  • Possessor thematicity (log text frequency)
  • Semnatics (prototypical vs. non-prototypical)
  • Type-token ratio
  • Prior genitive (s vs. other)

Analysis

Comparative sociolinguistic method

3 lines of evidence (Poplack & Tagliamonte 2001; Taglimonte 2002)

Looking across the registers…

  1. Which factors (constraints) are significant?
  2. How are factors ranked in terms of effect strength?
  3. What is the ordering of the levels within the factors (the effect direction)?

Differences in these lines of evidence would imply different grammars

Analysis: Identifying significant effects

Which factors are significant?

  • assess significance via mixed-effects logistic regression
    • by-author random intercepts (individual base rates)
    • by-author random slopes for possr animacy (individual constraint effects)
  • fit separate models to each register individually (predicting s-genitive)
    • identify which factors determine variant choice
    • examine direction (hierarchy) of contraint effects


Do the same factors significantly affect genitive choice in the different registers, in the same direction?

Analysis: Assessing relative strength

What is the relative contribution of factors across registers?

  • fit one model to combined dataset with same random factors
    • include interaction terms of internal constraints with Genre and Time (treatment coding with 'Press' as the reference level)
    • significant interaction terms are strong evidence variation in factor strength
  • compute variable importance rankings for individual register models
    • different rankings reflect different degrees of explanatory power-


Do certain factors vary in the strength of their effects by register?

  • use by-author slopes for animacy derived from the mixed-effects model (e.g. Forrest 2015)
  • do individuals' constraint effects match up to the aggregate patterns?
  • some variability is expected, but the direct of the effect should stay the same

Discussion

Register-specificity in genitives

  • Registers vary considerably…
    • in which factors influence genitive choice
    • in the relative importance of those factors
  • But, the effect directions (constraint hierarchies) are completely parallel across registers.
    • evidence of cognitive/functional processes at work?
  • Is this sufficient evidence to posit register-specific genitive grammar(s)?
    • a reasonable case could be made for written Press language as a distinct 'grammar'

Individual differences

"…most sociolinguistic, and social-semiotic variation [involves] rates of use. When the contexts of use differ, different grammars are involved." (Guy 2015)

  • we observe both different rates AND (some) different contexts across individuals
  • but individual variation in animacy effects only apparent in some registers
  • again, high degree of consistency among authors suggests the emergence of a unique Press grammar

Remaining questions

  • How can we define a threshold beyond which an individual's (or register's) constraint effects can be considered a reflection of a distinct grammar?
    • no two speakers ever have exactly the same experience, hence differences across individuals will always exist
    • at what point do differences become large enough to "notice" and become available for indexical purposes?
    • statistical significance is not a good metric
  • How can we investigate register sensitivity within individuals directly
    • same individual, different registers
    • corpus data are ill-suited for this

Remaining questions

To what extent are our models of different grammars dependent on the tools we use to identify them?

  • different analytical techniques can yield very different results… so which should we use?
  • how do we incorporate results of multiple, possibly conflicting, techniques into comparative sociolinguistics?
